'''Short Note:
Sum: The sum is the total of all the salary values in the ‘salary_in_usd’ column. 
It gives a sense of the total expenditure on salaries by the company.

Mean: The mean, often referred to as the average, is calculated by adding up all the salaries and then dividing by the number of salaries.
It gives a sense of the “typical” salary an employee might expect at the company.

Standard Deviation: The standard deviation measures the amount of variation or dispersion in the salaries.
If the standard deviation is small, it means that most of the salaries are close to the mean (average) salary.
If the standard deviation is large, it means the salaries are spread out over a wider range. 
This could indicate a significant wage gap within the company.

Skewness: Skewness measures the asymmetry of the salary distribution.
If the skewness is positive, it means the right tail of the distribution is longer or fatter than the left. 
In the context of salaries, positive skewness would indicate that most employees earn less than the average salary,
with a few employees earning significantly more. If the skewness is negative,
it means the left tail of the distribution is longer or fatter than the right, 
indicating that most employees earn more than the average salary, with a few employees earning significantly less.

Kurtosis: Kurtosis measures the “tailedness” of the salary distribution.
High kurtosis indicates that the data has heavy tails or outliers, which means there are a few employees with salaries significantly different from the rest.
Low kurtosis indicates that the data has light tails, or fewer outliers, which means the salaries of most employees are similar.
'''

In [94]:
'''
Identifying Relationships: Correlation can help identify relationships between variables. 
For example, the positive correlation between work_year and salary_in_usd suggests 
that employees with more years of work experience might have higher salaries.
This could be useful for HR in salary benchmarking and compensation planning.

Predictive Analytics: If a strong correlation exists between two variables, one could be used to predict the other.
For instance, if work_year and salary_in_usd had a very high positive correlation,
you might be able to predict an employee’s salary based on their years of work experience.

Risk Management: Negative correlations are often used in portfolio management to diversify investments and reduce risk.
If two investment assets are negatively correlated, when one performs poorly, the other is likely to perform well,
balancing the overall performance.

Optimization: Understanding correlations can help businesses optimize their operations.
For example, if remote_ratio (the ratio of remote work) is negatively correlated with work_year,
it might suggest that more experienced employees prefer less remote work. 
This insight could be used to optimize work arrangements and improve employee satisfaction.

# Create a box plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
box_dict = plt.boxplot(dataScience['salary_in_usd'], vert=True, patch_artist=True, notch=True, widths=0.35)

# Change outline color, fill color and linewidth of the boxes
for patch in box_dict['boxes']:
    # Change outline color
    patch.set(color='#4286f4', linewidth=2)
    # Change fill color
    patch.set(facecolor='#e0e0e0')

# Change color and linewidth of the whiskers
for whisker in box_dict['whiskers']:
    whisker.set(color='#4286f4', linewidth=2)

# Change color and linewidth of the caps
for cap in box_dict['caps']:
    cap.set(color='#4286f4', linewidth=2)

# Change color and linewidth of the medians
for median in box_dict['medians']:
    median.set(color='#b22222', linewidth=2)

# Change the style of fliers and their fill
for flier in box_dict['fliers']:
    flier.set(marker='o', color='#e7298a', alpha=1)

# Set labels
plt.title('Box Plot of Salaries', fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Salary in USD', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks([1], ['Salaries'], fontsize=12)

# Show the plot
plt.show()
